ce:section.ce:para:
The electrical tortuosity (
τ e
) is determined from experiments measuring the effective conductivity (
σ eff
) of a porous medium saturated with an electrolyte. The hindrance of the porous structure to the charge transport results in a lower effective conductivity compared to the bulk conductivity of the electrolyte [42]. The relationship between these conductivities can be expressed using Eq. (2) [18,43] and will be further discussed in Section 3.2.

In order to conveniently compare and quantify how the porosity and tortuosity affect the transport process in a porous medium, the effective transport coefficient (
                           δ
                        ), which is defined as the ratio of the porosity to the squared tortuosity (see the equation in Table 2
                        ) [8], is presented in this study. The effective transport coefficient is the inverse of the MacMullin number, which can be regarded as the normalisation of the effective conductivity. Table 2 shows comparisons of porosity, tortuosity and effective transport coefficient (
                           δ
                        ) values determined using different methods.
